We investigated if other {\it timing properties} can be used to observationally distinguish between the different metrics by 
analyzing the observable time lags between the direct corona emission and the reflected emission assuming the lamp post geometry.
We use the standard X-ray reverberation analysis methods described by \cite{Uttley2014}. As expected, 
the 2-10 keV flux variations lag the 1-2 keV flux variations (Figure \ref{fig:lag}). 
	The JP metric leads to time lags up to 24\% shorter than the 
Kerr and KN metrics at low frequencies.  At frequencies between 0.01 $c/r_g$ and 0.1 $c/r_g$  
phase wrapping begins to occur (when the lag changes sign and begins to oscillate around 0) 
leading to the larger differences seen in this range.

